WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.568 --> 00:00:07.160
GRETCHEN RUBIN: "The Happiness
Project"-- the way I think

00:00:07.160 --> 00:00:10.620
about it-- is just any kind of
systematic attempt to think

00:00:10.620 --> 00:00:11.650
about happiness.

00:00:11.650 --> 00:00:14.770
Because what I found for myself
was that until I really

00:00:14.770 --> 00:00:17.610
started to think about it,
I never thought about

00:00:17.610 --> 00:00:19.570
happiness at all.

00:00:19.570 --> 00:00:21.990
I never asked myself whether
I was happy or

00:00:21.990 --> 00:00:23.200
how I could be happier.

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:26.130
And so with "The Happiness
Project" I really set out to

00:00:26.130 --> 00:00:29.600
ask myself well, what are the
things that make me happy?

00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:30.730
How can I be happier?

00:00:30.730 --> 00:00:33.480
And what are the small,
manageable, realistic changes

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:34.710
that I could make in my life?

00:00:34.710 --> 00:00:36.490
So I went about it a very
particular way.

00:00:36.490 --> 00:00:39.870
So I gave every month a theme,
and I had several resolutions

00:00:39.870 --> 00:00:41.000
related to every theme.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:44.140
Whether it was energy, or
marriage, or friendship, or

00:00:44.140 --> 00:00:46.180
play, or whatever.

00:00:46.180 --> 00:00:48.670
But then people can do it
all different ways.

00:00:48.670 --> 00:00:50.720
One kind of Happiness
Project that I love

00:00:50.720 --> 00:00:53.370
is people who pick--

00:00:53.370 --> 00:00:55.300
and I did I've done
this myself now--

00:00:55.300 --> 00:01:02.810
one word theme for a year to
give your year a driving idea.

00:01:02.810 --> 00:01:07.090
So I picked the word
bigger as my team.

00:01:07.090 --> 00:01:10.160
My sister pick the
word smaller.

00:01:10.160 --> 00:01:13.010
And they both are
great themes.

00:01:13.010 --> 00:01:18.460
I have a friend who one of his
themes was fame, and one of

00:01:18.460 --> 00:01:20.720
his other themes was dark.

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:23.660
So you can get a picture
of what he's like.

00:01:23.660 --> 00:01:26.720
And so that's another way to
do a Happiness Project.

00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:31.530
There's a very prevalent
and highly

00:01:31.530 --> 00:01:33.570
estimable theme in happiness.

00:01:33.570 --> 00:01:36.830
Which is to say, if you try to
be happier you'll trip over

00:01:36.830 --> 00:01:37.580
your own feet.

00:01:37.580 --> 00:01:40.210
So John Stuart Mill said ask
yourself if you are happy, and

00:01:40.210 --> 00:01:41.570
you shall cease to be so.

00:01:41.570 --> 00:01:44.420
So it's this idea that you can't
really try to be happy

00:01:44.420 --> 00:01:46.320
it has to happen indirectly.

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:48.830
And I hate to go up against John
Stuart Mill and Eleanor

00:01:48.830 --> 00:01:49.870
Roosevelt, and many others.

00:01:49.870 --> 00:01:52.090
But I really do not find
that to be true.

00:01:52.090 --> 00:01:55.930
I find that actually thinking
about it is helpful.

00:01:55.930 --> 00:01:58.260
Because it's by really directly
thinking about it,

00:01:58.260 --> 00:01:59.580
and saying well, what's
not working?

00:01:59.580 --> 00:02:00.750
How can I be happier?

00:02:00.750 --> 00:02:03.610
That's when I started to really
identify places where I

00:02:03.610 --> 00:02:06.380
could imagine making changes
that would make me happier.

00:02:06.380 --> 00:02:11.560
So for me that's what doing a
happiness project The means.

00:02:11.560 --> 00:02:16.810
SHAREE: And one thing that you
mentioned was very empowering.

00:02:16.810 --> 00:02:18.630
To think of happiness as
something that you can

00:02:18.630 --> 00:02:21.790
actually work towards, and
take small steps towards.

00:02:21.790 --> 00:02:25.390
That's a very empowering way
to look at happiness.

00:02:25.390 --> 00:02:27.660
Unlike the roundabout way
of getting to happiness.

00:02:27.660 --> 00:02:28.590
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Right, right.

00:02:28.590 --> 00:02:31.040
Well, and it's interesting
because one of the questions

00:02:31.040 --> 00:02:34.320
is how much is it within
your control?

00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:38.150
And it turns out that
researchers think that about

00:02:38.150 --> 00:02:40.930
50% of happiness is genetically
determined.

00:02:40.930 --> 00:02:43.750
So some people are born Tiggers,
and some people are

00:02:43.750 --> 00:02:44.620
born Eeyores.

00:02:44.620 --> 00:02:46.340
And we've all seen that.

00:02:46.340 --> 00:02:47.600
It's pretty hard wired.

00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:49.750
Then about 10 to 20% is
something called life

00:02:49.750 --> 00:02:50.660
circumstances.

00:02:50.660 --> 00:02:55.720
Which is age, occupation,
marital status, education,

00:02:55.720 --> 00:02:58.440
income, health, things
like that.

00:02:58.440 --> 00:03:01.600
Which you maybe have some
control over, but those are

00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:02.930
more like life circumstances.

00:03:02.930 --> 00:03:05.760
And then all the rest is very
much within our conscious

00:03:05.760 --> 00:03:08.970
control and is affected by the
way that we think and the way

00:03:08.970 --> 00:03:09.770
that we act.

00:03:09.770 --> 00:03:12.440
So depending on where your
range is, you can push

00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:14.760
yourself up to the top of your
range, or push yourself down

00:03:14.760 --> 00:03:17.460
to the bottom of your range
by the way that

00:03:17.460 --> 00:03:18.480
you think and act.

00:03:18.480 --> 00:03:22.140
And so it isn't just that
it's flowing over you.

00:03:22.140 --> 00:03:26.150
To some extent it's not
completely within your control

00:03:26.150 --> 00:03:27.940
to change your nature.

00:03:27.940 --> 00:03:30.450
But there are things that you
can do to get yourself up to

00:03:30.450 --> 00:03:33.700
the top of that range instead of
floating down at the bottom

00:03:33.700 --> 00:03:35.075
part of your range.

00:03:35.075 --> 00:03:38.680
SHAREE: That's definitely
good to know.

00:03:38.680 --> 00:03:41.460
You also mentioned in your
first book a concept of a

00:03:41.460 --> 00:03:42.710
happiness formula.

00:03:42.710 --> 00:03:46.580
And most people think of
happiness as things that make

00:03:46.580 --> 00:03:48.740
me feel good, and then things
that make me feel bad, and how

00:03:48.740 --> 00:03:52.310
to reduce the ones that make me
feel bad and increase the

00:03:52.310 --> 00:03:53.170
ones that make me feel good.

00:03:53.170 --> 00:03:55.380
But you bring up an interesting
point about

00:03:55.380 --> 00:03:58.800
feeling right, and about the
atmosphere of growth.

00:03:58.800 --> 00:04:02.560
Which, as an adult, I didn't
really think about.

00:04:02.560 --> 00:04:04.450
The feeling right part I
understood to an extent.

00:04:04.450 --> 00:04:05.450
But the growth part,

00:04:05.450 --> 00:04:09.280
surprisingly, I missed entirely.

00:04:09.280 --> 00:04:11.760
Can you elaborate on these
two aspects and

00:04:11.760 --> 00:04:12.860
why they're so important?

00:04:12.860 --> 00:04:14.485
Well I completely missed
the atmosphere of

00:04:14.485 --> 00:04:16.300
growth at first too.

00:04:16.300 --> 00:04:20.149
Because I was trying to come
up with my framework for

00:04:20.149 --> 00:04:23.340
understanding happiness, or
thinking about how I wanted a

00:04:23.340 --> 00:04:26.830
framework where every little
piece fit into the puzzle

00:04:26.830 --> 00:04:29.650
somehow, that there was nothing
left on the floor.

00:04:29.650 --> 00:04:33.210
And so I came up with that to
think about happiness you have

00:04:33.210 --> 00:04:35.960
to think about feeling good,
feeling bad, feeling right, in

00:04:35.960 --> 00:04:37.300
an atmosphere of growth.

00:04:37.300 --> 00:04:40.630
And atmosphere of growth took
me much longer to identify.

00:04:40.630 --> 00:04:42.010
So the feeling good is easy.

00:04:42.010 --> 00:04:44.570
You want things that make you
feel full of enthusiasm, and

00:04:44.570 --> 00:04:46.910
love, and fun.

00:04:46.910 --> 00:04:48.670
And feeling bad, you want to
get rid of things that make

00:04:48.670 --> 00:04:53.320
you feel angry, or resentful,
or guilty, or jealous.

00:04:53.320 --> 00:04:56.670
And then feeling right
is trickier.

00:04:56.670 --> 00:05:01.440
Because feeling right is the
feeling that our life reflects

00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:05.470
our values, and that we're
living up to our own idea of

00:05:05.470 --> 00:05:07.520
what we want our life to be.

00:05:07.520 --> 00:05:10.820
And this is complicated, because
sometimes the things

00:05:10.820 --> 00:05:13.590
that we do to make ourselves
feel right don't

00:05:13.590 --> 00:05:14.950
make us feel good.

00:05:14.950 --> 00:05:21.330
For instance I was talking to a
guy to who was one of three

00:05:21.330 --> 00:05:22.820
brothers, adults.

00:05:22.820 --> 00:05:24.490
And they were very estranged.

00:05:24.490 --> 00:05:27.570
They had a father who was
very nasty, apparently.

00:05:27.570 --> 00:05:29.560
To the extent that two of the
sons wouldn't speak to the

00:05:29.560 --> 00:05:30.760
father anymore.

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:35.380
And the father was in the
hospital, and the one son was

00:05:35.380 --> 00:05:36.150
going and visiting him.

00:05:36.150 --> 00:05:37.960
And he said the thing
is, it doesn't do

00:05:37.960 --> 00:05:39.440
anything for my happiness.

00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:41.560
I hate going, I dread
going, he's mean

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:42.280
to me when I'm there.

00:05:42.280 --> 00:05:45.760
He's been mean to me my whole
life, and yet here I am going.

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:49.050
And I said well it's because
it's making you feel right.

00:05:49.050 --> 00:05:51.450
This is your idea of how you
should behave as a son.

00:05:51.450 --> 00:05:53.800
And even though it doesn't make
you feel good, it makes

00:05:53.800 --> 00:05:54.910
you feel right.

00:05:54.910 --> 00:05:57.940
And sometimes that's important
to happiness as well, even if

00:05:57.940 --> 00:05:59.760
it doesn't translate
into feeling good.

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:02.080
And then atmosphere of growth
is a little bit different.

00:06:02.080 --> 00:06:05.140
And this is the feeling that
people are happier when we

00:06:05.140 --> 00:06:06.590
feel like we're growing.

00:06:06.590 --> 00:06:09.020
When we're learning something,
when we're changing something

00:06:09.020 --> 00:06:11.140
for the better, when we're
fixing something, when we're

00:06:11.140 --> 00:06:13.580
helping someone.

00:06:13.580 --> 00:06:15.650
And it could be something as
simple as cleaning out your

00:06:15.650 --> 00:06:16.940
refrigerator--

00:06:16.940 --> 00:06:18.790
can give you that little
feeling of growth.

00:06:18.790 --> 00:06:21.310
Or learning something new.

00:06:21.310 --> 00:06:23.020
I'm sure we've all had the
experience of when you're

00:06:23.020 --> 00:06:24.830
trying to learn something
new and it's incredibly

00:06:24.830 --> 00:06:25.370
frustrating.

00:06:25.370 --> 00:06:28.780
You feel stupid, you feeling
incompetent.

00:06:28.780 --> 00:06:31.730
And yet then when you manage
to grow and you managed to

00:06:31.730 --> 00:06:34.450
learn something it's
so satisfying.

00:06:34.450 --> 00:06:37.100
And the thing that's nice about
the atmosphere of growth

00:06:37.100 --> 00:06:39.870
is this is really something that
you can deliberately go

00:06:39.870 --> 00:06:41.190
out and pursue.

00:06:41.190 --> 00:06:44.240
You can really say to yourself
wow, I'm really in an unhappy

00:06:44.240 --> 00:06:45.050
place in my life.

00:06:45.050 --> 00:06:49.150
I have a lot going on that's
making me just feel terrible,

00:06:49.150 --> 00:06:51.680
and I need to find
a way to plug my

00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:52.800
battery into something.

00:06:52.800 --> 00:06:53.890
What can I do?

00:06:53.890 --> 00:06:55.910
And a way to do it is to seek
the atmosphere of growth.

00:06:55.910 --> 00:07:02.140
Whether it's getting a pet and
house training your pet, or

00:07:02.140 --> 00:07:05.770
fixing something, or helping an
organization figure out how

00:07:05.770 --> 00:07:09.730
to do their books better, or
helping a friend move, or

00:07:09.730 --> 00:07:12.000
cleaning out your closet,
or learning a

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:13.300
new software program.

00:07:13.300 --> 00:07:20.380
This atmosphere of growth is
something that is energizing,

00:07:20.380 --> 00:07:25.050
and in a way that's very,
very positive.

00:07:25.050 --> 00:07:27.300
However, a lot of times
it does come with this

00:07:27.300 --> 00:07:30.040
unfortunate layer of feeling
stupid, incompetent,

00:07:30.040 --> 00:07:31.660
frustrated, having to
work with annoying

00:07:31.660 --> 00:07:33.440
people, all that stuff.

00:07:33.440 --> 00:07:35.700
So you have to accept that
sometimes feeling bad is part

00:07:35.700 --> 00:07:37.820
of happiness.

00:07:37.820 --> 00:07:42.410
SHAREE: It's also interesting
that the atmosphere of growth

00:07:42.410 --> 00:07:46.410
part is probably something we
need most when we are down.

00:07:46.410 --> 00:07:48.710
And that's probably when we
are least likely to even

00:07:48.710 --> 00:07:50.226
attempt it.

00:07:50.226 --> 00:07:51.360
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yes.

00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:53.730
Annette, you raise a very
interesting point, which is

00:07:53.730 --> 00:07:57.160
that one of the reasons that
I wanted to do a happiness

00:07:57.160 --> 00:08:00.500
project was that I felt like I
would behave myself better if

00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:01.830
I were happier.

00:08:01.830 --> 00:08:04.630
And I find that definitely
to be true.

00:08:04.630 --> 00:08:09.300
I'm more patient, I'm more
forgiving, I'm less irascible,

00:08:09.300 --> 00:08:12.870
I'm more generous when
I'm happier.

00:08:12.870 --> 00:08:16.290
And studies show that although
happiness has this bad

00:08:16.290 --> 00:08:18.710
reputation, and some people
assume that happy people are

00:08:18.710 --> 00:08:22.010
smug, or superficial,
or stupid.

00:08:22.010 --> 00:08:24.550
Actually, happy people are
more interested in the

00:08:24.550 --> 00:08:26.930
problems of other people, and
more interested in the

00:08:26.930 --> 00:08:27.790
problems of the world.

00:08:27.790 --> 00:08:29.490
They're more altruistic, they
give away more money, they

00:08:29.490 --> 00:08:31.560
volunteer more time, they're
more likely to help out their

00:08:31.560 --> 00:08:34.530
colleagues and their friends
and their family.

00:08:34.530 --> 00:08:36.789
And I think when you are happier
you do you feel more

00:08:36.789 --> 00:08:40.250
able to try to do something
that's going to bring you that

00:08:40.250 --> 00:08:42.110
atmosphere of growth even if
there's going to be a lot of

00:08:42.110 --> 00:08:46.370
frustration or anxiety
attached to it.

00:08:46.370 --> 00:08:49.140
But when you're not feeling
happy it can feel overwhelming

00:08:49.140 --> 00:08:50.660
to try to plug into that.

00:08:50.660 --> 00:08:52.530
And it's the same thing with
helping other people.

00:08:52.530 --> 00:08:54.900
One of the best ways to make
yourself happy is to make

00:08:54.900 --> 00:08:56.340
other people happy.

00:08:56.340 --> 00:08:58.370
But sometimes when you're
feeling very unhappy yourself

00:08:58.370 --> 00:09:00.670
you don't have the emotional
wherewithal to do it.

00:09:00.670 --> 00:09:02.480
And so even though it would make
you feel better if you

00:09:02.480 --> 00:09:07.270
did it, it's hard to get
yourself to do it.

00:09:07.270 --> 00:09:09.830
So I think it's worth
understanding that.

00:09:09.830 --> 00:09:12.430
So then if you are an unhappy
place and you feel like oh, I

00:09:12.430 --> 00:09:15.540
just I just can't handle the
thought of learning how to do

00:09:15.540 --> 00:09:17.660
something new.

00:09:17.660 --> 00:09:20.100
If you say to yourself it's
going to be hard, but in the

00:09:20.100 --> 00:09:22.310
end I'm going to get that
charge, I'm going to get that

00:09:22.310 --> 00:09:24.940
feeling of uplift.

00:09:24.940 --> 00:09:28.280
Then maybe that can help
you push yourself.

00:09:28.280 --> 00:09:31.410
Because you know that in the and
it's going to be helpful,

00:09:31.410 --> 00:09:32.870
especially if you're in
a difficult time.

00:09:32.870 --> 00:09:36.460
SHAREE: So it's about being
conscious of that behavior?

00:09:36.460 --> 00:09:37.960
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yeah, I
think it really helps.

00:09:37.960 --> 00:09:41.050
SHAREE: Another thing that you
mentioned in your first book

00:09:41.050 --> 00:09:44.580
is how "The Happiness Project"
could potentially prepare

00:09:44.580 --> 00:09:48.370
people for when bad things
actually do happen.

00:09:48.370 --> 00:09:49.960
Would you like to elaborate
on that?

00:09:49.960 --> 00:09:50.860
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yeah, when I
was writing "The Happiness

00:09:50.860 --> 00:09:56.560
Project" I was worried, because
I thought I was a

00:09:56.560 --> 00:09:58.200
pretty happy person
when I started.

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:00.720
And I had a great life, and one
of the things I wanted to

00:10:00.720 --> 00:10:03.620
do was to appreciate it more and
not take it for granted.

00:10:03.620 --> 00:10:06.760
And I worried that people who
were facing major happiness

00:10:06.760 --> 00:10:11.020
challenges would find what I
was writing about trivial

00:10:11.020 --> 00:10:13.720
almost to the point
of offensiveness.

00:10:13.720 --> 00:10:16.340
I'm talking about make your
bed, and someone else is

00:10:16.340 --> 00:10:20.670
thinking about they just lost
two family members to cancer

00:10:20.670 --> 00:10:22.820
in the same month.

00:10:22.820 --> 00:10:26.620
And so I was concerned
about that.

00:10:26.620 --> 00:10:31.320
But what I found is I've heard
from so many people who are in

00:10:31.320 --> 00:10:35.020
these very, very challenging
situations.

00:10:35.020 --> 00:10:37.960
And they have made
this point to me.

00:10:37.960 --> 00:10:41.230
Which is that one time to do a
happiness project is really

00:10:41.230 --> 00:10:43.980
when you are in a very
challenging situation, and

00:10:43.980 --> 00:10:46.880
you're really struggling to
figure out how can you be as

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:49.310
happy as you can be under
the circumstances?

00:10:49.310 --> 00:10:51.030
Maybe you can't be happy,
but are you as

00:10:51.030 --> 00:10:52.600
happy as you can be?

00:10:52.600 --> 00:10:54.070
Can you make sure you
get enough sleep?

00:10:54.070 --> 00:10:55.650
Can you make sure that
eat regularly?

00:10:55.650 --> 00:10:57.140
Can you make sure that
you see your friends?

00:10:57.140 --> 00:10:59.980
Can you make sure that you give
yourself mental breaks

00:10:59.980 --> 00:11:01.430
from whatever the
situation is?

00:11:01.430 --> 00:11:04.160
So that you don't burn
yourself out

00:11:04.160 --> 00:11:05.630
dealing with some crisis.

00:11:05.630 --> 00:11:07.540
But then another time to do
it is when everything is

00:11:07.540 --> 00:11:10.310
basically going OK, and you do
have the emotional wherewithal

00:11:10.310 --> 00:11:16.790
to try to start a book group,
or start exercising.

00:11:16.790 --> 00:11:22.530
Or figure out ways so that you
can be yelling at your kids

00:11:22.530 --> 00:11:23.500
less or whatever.

00:11:23.500 --> 00:11:25.730
And so I think there's a
reason to do it when

00:11:25.730 --> 00:11:27.960
everything's going fine, and
there's a reason to do it when

00:11:27.960 --> 00:11:30.830
really everything is not fine,
and you're just hanging on by

00:11:30.830 --> 00:11:32.240
your fingernails.

00:11:32.240 --> 00:11:36.090
So it was encouraging for me
to hear that people didn't

00:11:36.090 --> 00:11:42.650
find my focus on these very
ordinary little parts of life

00:11:42.650 --> 00:11:46.572
to be deeply annoying,
as I feared.

00:11:46.572 --> 00:11:48.870
SHAREE: Cool.

00:11:48.870 --> 00:11:52.400
You also mention in your book
that it's important to follow

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:53.810
your true nature.

00:11:53.810 --> 00:11:55.930
And at the same time you
immediately follow it up by

00:11:55.930 --> 00:11:58.740
saying it's important to also
distinguish between the lack

00:11:58.740 --> 00:12:02.470
of interest and the
fear of failure.

00:12:02.470 --> 00:12:04.010
Now how do you make
that distinction?

00:12:04.010 --> 00:12:06.106
Because that's a really
good skill to have.

00:12:06.106 --> 00:12:08.060
GRETCHEN RUBIN: So you put
your finger on the big

00:12:08.060 --> 00:12:10.110
challenges within happiness.

00:12:10.110 --> 00:12:13.200
Because on the one hand, you
want to accept yourself, but

00:12:13.200 --> 00:12:15.620
you also want to expect
more from yourself.

00:12:15.620 --> 00:12:17.330
And this is just a
constant tension.

00:12:17.330 --> 00:12:20.170
This is like the tension between
being happy in the

00:12:20.170 --> 00:12:21.640
moment and thinking
about the future.

00:12:25.540 --> 00:12:27.320
You have to think about
both all the time

00:12:27.320 --> 00:12:28.630
and make your decisions.

00:12:28.630 --> 00:12:30.920
There's not one easy
way to do it.

00:12:30.920 --> 00:12:33.240
I have 12 personal commandments
that I identified

00:12:33.240 --> 00:12:34.430
as part of my happiness
projects.

00:12:34.430 --> 00:12:37.470
And the first one is
to be Gretchen.

00:12:37.470 --> 00:12:41.090
And everyone should feel free to
substitute there own name.

00:12:41.090 --> 00:12:44.630
And there's this idea that you
have to be yourself, and to

00:12:44.630 --> 00:12:46.270
know yourself.

00:12:46.270 --> 00:12:50.510
And part of what's hard about
that is that it's very easy to

00:12:50.510 --> 00:12:53.290
think about the way you wish you
were, or the way you think

00:12:53.290 --> 00:12:55.550
you ought to be, or the way
other people want you to be,

00:12:55.550 --> 00:12:58.990
and to lose sight of the
way you really are.

00:12:58.990 --> 00:13:00.530
Well like I said, I went
to law school.

00:13:00.530 --> 00:13:03.620
I was a lawyer for five
years without even

00:13:03.620 --> 00:13:05.080
thinking about it.

00:13:05.080 --> 00:13:08.840
So I really have to remind
myself to be Gretchen.

00:13:08.840 --> 00:13:11.390
And one of the questions within
trying to be yourself

00:13:11.390 --> 00:13:15.080
is when are you setting
yourself a task that's

00:13:15.080 --> 00:13:18.330
appropriate for you and is
within your own nature, and is

00:13:18.330 --> 00:13:20.330
pushing you in the right
direction to

00:13:20.330 --> 00:13:22.050
expect more from yourself?

00:13:22.050 --> 00:13:27.000
And when are you really picking
something for the

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:27.760
wrong reasons?

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:30.090
Or not because it's really
meaningful to you but it's

00:13:30.090 --> 00:13:34.350
related to a fantasy of who you
think you are, or the way

00:13:34.350 --> 00:13:35.760
you wish you would be.

00:13:35.760 --> 00:13:40.300
And it isn't a natural extension
of your personality.

00:13:40.300 --> 00:13:44.760
It's not the right
goal for you.

00:13:44.760 --> 00:13:47.710
And those things tend
to be very sterile.

00:13:47.710 --> 00:13:52.500
It's very easy to burn out, or
to hit a dead end with that.

00:13:52.500 --> 00:13:55.330
I recently faced this
with driving.

00:13:55.330 --> 00:13:57.730
Is anybody here a
fearful driver?

00:13:57.730 --> 00:13:58.930
I'm a fearful driver.

00:13:58.930 --> 00:14:00.180
OK.

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:03.500
So I grew up in Kansas
City, Missouri.

00:14:03.500 --> 00:14:05.430
So I got a driver's license
when I was 16

00:14:05.430 --> 00:14:06.400
years old, and I drove.

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:08.050
And when I lived in Washington,
DC, I drove.

00:14:10.600 --> 00:14:12.030
But I always a fearful driver.

00:14:12.030 --> 00:14:15.000
And my sister lived in LA for
three years before she drove,

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:18.940
so you see where I'm
coming from.

00:14:18.940 --> 00:14:23.280
And we were living in New York,
and basically any time

00:14:23.280 --> 00:14:25.440
we had to drive my husband
would drive.

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:27.750
To the point where I basically
quit driving.

00:14:27.750 --> 00:14:30.590
And we weren't driving
that much.

00:14:30.590 --> 00:14:33.830
But we were driving to Vermont
to pick up my daughter from

00:14:33.830 --> 00:14:37.030
summer camp, and I
was not driving.

00:14:37.030 --> 00:14:41.460
And I felt like that was an
unfair burden on my husband.

00:14:41.460 --> 00:14:43.960
Because even if he got tired
or had to take a conference

00:14:43.960 --> 00:14:45.990
call or something,
he had to drive.

00:14:45.990 --> 00:14:48.460
And, also, I was beginning
to feel like it was

00:14:48.460 --> 00:14:49.330
weighing on my mind.

00:14:49.330 --> 00:14:52.110
I started having dreams where
there would be an emergency

00:14:52.110 --> 00:14:55.040
and I wouldn't be able to go
because I couldn't drive.

00:14:55.040 --> 00:15:01.200
And I had to ask myself is
being a fearful driver

00:15:01.200 --> 00:15:04.530
something that I should accept
about myself as just being

00:15:04.530 --> 00:15:05.580
part of my true nature?

00:15:05.580 --> 00:15:08.250
And has been true of me for as
long as I can remember, and so

00:15:08.250 --> 00:15:09.830
just accept it?

00:15:09.830 --> 00:15:13.570
Or can I expect more from
myself, and deal with this

00:15:13.570 --> 00:15:14.750
fear of driving?

00:15:14.750 --> 00:15:17.430
And I so desperately wanted to
believe that I should just

00:15:17.430 --> 00:15:19.960
accept it, and not
drive ever again.

00:15:19.960 --> 00:15:22.390
But I did decide that it was
something where I could ask

00:15:22.390 --> 00:15:24.150
myself to do it.

00:15:24.150 --> 00:15:29.110
So now I drive regularly, and I
really do not like driving,

00:15:29.110 --> 00:15:30.890
but I do drive.

00:15:30.890 --> 00:15:34.260
And it's been interesting for
me to hear a lot of people

00:15:34.260 --> 00:15:37.380
have something in their life
that they're afraid to do,

00:15:37.380 --> 00:15:39.490
that other people do
without thinking.

00:15:39.490 --> 00:15:45.960
Riding a bike, public speaking,
swimming, flying.

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:49.240
These are things, for most
people, it doesn't seem like

00:15:49.240 --> 00:15:49.860
it bothers them.

00:15:49.860 --> 00:15:51.430
And then there's the people
for whom it's really

00:15:51.430 --> 00:15:54.630
difficult, and you really have
to say to yourself, do I want

00:15:54.630 --> 00:15:57.640
to expect of myself?

00:15:57.640 --> 00:15:59.280
But then there's other
things, like music.

00:15:59.280 --> 00:16:00.150
I finally said you know what?

00:16:00.150 --> 00:16:01.670
I don't really like music.

00:16:01.670 --> 00:16:04.170
I used to think oh, if I would
just go to concerts, if I

00:16:04.170 --> 00:16:06.360
would read, if I would study
up, if I would sit down and

00:16:06.360 --> 00:16:08.590
listen and concentrate I
would love music too.

00:16:08.590 --> 00:16:09.710
And finally, I'm like
you know what?

00:16:09.710 --> 00:16:12.120
I'm just don't like
music that much.

00:16:12.120 --> 00:16:13.150
And I'm sad about that.

00:16:13.150 --> 00:16:13.880
I wish I did.

00:16:13.880 --> 00:16:18.430
I see why everybody
else likes it.

00:16:18.430 --> 00:16:19.870
And I wish I like it.

00:16:19.870 --> 00:16:23.070
I wish I could be Gretchen and
love music, and tap into this

00:16:23.070 --> 00:16:25.960
source of joy that so
many people feel.

00:16:25.960 --> 00:16:29.480
But I finally had to just say
yeah, I got to accept myself.

00:16:29.480 --> 00:16:32.020
And it's just not for me.

00:16:32.020 --> 00:16:34.140
And now that I don't worry about
loving music I have more

00:16:34.140 --> 00:16:36.460
time to do the things I like.

00:16:36.460 --> 00:16:39.740
Like read all the time.

00:16:39.740 --> 00:16:42.660
So its attention to accept
yourself and

00:16:42.660 --> 00:16:44.476
expect more of yourself.

00:16:44.476 --> 00:16:46.730
SHAREE: So along the same lines,
how have you seen your

00:16:46.730 --> 00:16:50.350
personality change as you've
gone through the several

00:16:50.350 --> 00:16:51.730
happiness projects?

00:16:51.730 --> 00:16:54.860
And obviously you like the
way your personality has

00:16:54.860 --> 00:16:55.760
changed, if it has.

00:16:55.760 --> 00:16:56.770
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Well
it's interesting.

00:16:56.770 --> 00:17:00.000
Because when I started I took
one of those tests.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:01.460
Which, by the way,
drive me crazy.

00:17:01.460 --> 00:17:03.670
I hate the tests to tell
how happy you are,

00:17:03.670 --> 00:17:06.390
but I score a seven.

00:17:06.390 --> 00:17:07.960
I'm pretty happy.

00:17:07.960 --> 00:17:11.839
And most people around the world
will say that they are

00:17:11.839 --> 00:17:13.349
pretty happy, or very happy.

00:17:13.349 --> 00:17:15.339
So most people are pretty happy,
and I'm pretty happy.

00:17:15.339 --> 00:17:16.589
So I'm average.

00:17:19.250 --> 00:17:21.970
And so the interesting thing
for me is that is, I would

00:17:21.970 --> 00:17:23.119
say, is my inborn nature.

00:17:23.119 --> 00:17:26.099
And if I am lying in bed at
night or I'm on the subway

00:17:26.099 --> 00:17:29.460
with nothing to read, and I'm
just staring out into space, I

00:17:29.460 --> 00:17:31.810
am at a seven place.

00:17:31.810 --> 00:17:33.940
More or less, usually.

00:17:33.940 --> 00:17:36.200
I'm not in a highly ebullient
person, but I'm not a

00:17:36.200 --> 00:17:36.750
melancholic person.

00:17:36.750 --> 00:17:38.200
I'm just a seven.

00:17:38.200 --> 00:17:40.660
But what has changed as a result
of doing the happiness

00:17:40.660 --> 00:17:44.360
project is that my experience of
my life is so much happier.

00:17:44.360 --> 00:17:47.250
I spend so much less time
feeling angry, or

00:17:47.250 --> 00:17:48.650
resentful, or bored.

00:17:48.650 --> 00:17:51.520
And I spend so much more time
having fun and doing the

00:17:51.520 --> 00:17:53.260
things I value.

00:17:53.260 --> 00:17:55.420
Like not worrying about music.

00:17:58.570 --> 00:18:02.570
And so even though you can't
change your inborn nature, you

00:18:02.570 --> 00:18:03.940
can change the experience
of your life.

00:18:03.940 --> 00:18:06.350
And I think the best example
of this-- which I'm sure

00:18:06.350 --> 00:18:07.060
everybody has seen--

00:18:07.060 --> 00:18:10.300
is if you've ever had a job that
you really hated you're

00:18:10.300 --> 00:18:12.870
still yourself.

00:18:12.870 --> 00:18:15.260
You're still walking around as
yourself, but your experience

00:18:15.260 --> 00:18:16.550
of your life is very
different.

00:18:16.550 --> 00:18:18.940
And then if you get a job that
you love, it's like you're the

00:18:18.940 --> 00:18:19.570
same person.

00:18:19.570 --> 00:18:21.950
Probably your life circumstances
haven't changed

00:18:21.950 --> 00:18:24.020
very much, and maybe
not at all.

00:18:24.020 --> 00:18:25.760
But your experience of your
life is so much happier

00:18:25.760 --> 00:18:27.870
because you're doing something
that you enjoy.

00:18:27.870 --> 00:18:29.440
So that's what I think
has happened.

00:18:29.440 --> 00:18:30.490
I'm the same person.

00:18:30.490 --> 00:18:32.330
My personality is the same.

00:18:32.330 --> 00:18:35.280
But I just feel like
my experience

00:18:35.280 --> 00:18:36.590
of my life has changed.

00:18:43.080 --> 00:18:44.630
Mostly with things that
didn't take very much

00:18:44.630 --> 00:18:45.890
time, energy, or money.

00:18:45.890 --> 00:18:47.610
There's a lot of low-hanging
fruit.

00:18:47.610 --> 00:18:50.336
At least there was in my case.

00:18:50.336 --> 00:18:54.800
SHAREE: So how much of the
recording and tracking of the

00:18:54.800 --> 00:18:59.030
goals, and the resolutions
impacts the way you perceive

00:18:59.030 --> 00:18:59.920
your happiness?

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:02.690
And did it change between the
time you were actually going

00:19:02.690 --> 00:19:04.990
through the project, the 12
months, and then after?

00:19:04.990 --> 00:19:06.290
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Well, the
tracking is funny.

00:19:06.290 --> 00:19:08.030
Because actually,
Marcus Mitchell,

00:19:08.030 --> 00:19:08.870
who works at Google--

00:19:08.870 --> 00:19:10.700
I just saw him, but he had
to go somewhere else.

00:19:10.700 --> 00:19:12.590
When he heard about this he
was like well I think you

00:19:12.590 --> 00:19:13.790
should have your husband--

00:19:13.790 --> 00:19:15.070
they went to college together--
you should have

00:19:15.070 --> 00:19:19.490
Jamie score you on a one to
10 scale twice a day.

00:19:19.490 --> 00:19:20.250
Then you'd have a record.

00:19:20.250 --> 00:19:23.630
And I'm like yeah, that's
not going to happen.

00:19:23.630 --> 00:19:26.410
Yeah, so there are all these
quantified self, and they're

00:19:26.410 --> 00:19:29.230
all people who love to track.

00:19:29.230 --> 00:19:31.250
I like to track whether I'm
keeping my resolutions.

00:19:31.250 --> 00:19:34.180
So I like to track whether I'm
actually sticking to the

00:19:34.180 --> 00:19:35.930
things that I'm doing.

00:19:35.930 --> 00:19:37.560
I'm a junkie for gold stars.

00:19:37.560 --> 00:19:39.640
So I like checking things
off the list, and

00:19:39.640 --> 00:19:41.670
feeling yes I did it.

00:19:41.670 --> 00:19:44.000
So I do it in that way, but I
don't track it in terms of my

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:44.940
happiness level.

00:19:44.940 --> 00:19:48.320
Because for me, at least, I
find that to be intensely

00:19:48.320 --> 00:19:52.490
annoying, and actually if I
stand around I think am I

00:19:52.490 --> 00:19:53.740
happy right now?

00:19:55.960 --> 00:19:57.980
It sort of dissolves under me.

00:19:57.980 --> 00:20:00.720
I feel like it's more helpful to
think about being happier.

00:20:00.720 --> 00:20:02.290
Like is this going to
make me happier?

00:20:02.290 --> 00:20:04.040
Am I happier than I
was a month ago?

00:20:04.040 --> 00:20:06.540
So am I moving in the
right direction?

00:20:06.540 --> 00:20:08.990
So I think about more like that,
are things moving in the

00:20:08.990 --> 00:20:10.470
right direction?

00:20:10.470 --> 00:20:14.330
Than what's my actual ranking
right now, or how would I

00:20:14.330 --> 00:20:15.110
measure it?

00:20:15.110 --> 00:20:20.680
Because I do feel like
that can trip me up.

00:20:20.680 --> 00:20:22.760
But accountability for

00:20:22.760 --> 00:20:25.180
following through is important.

00:20:25.180 --> 00:20:27.250
And I do think one thing--

00:20:27.250 --> 00:20:29.400
when people are thinking about
happiness projects for

00:20:29.400 --> 00:20:30.890
themselves--

00:20:30.890 --> 00:20:34.390
one thing I think is helpful to
remember is that it works

00:20:34.390 --> 00:20:38.040
better when you think of
change in terms of very

00:20:38.040 --> 00:20:41.810
concrete, very manageable
actions.

00:20:41.810 --> 00:20:45.130
So sometimes people will say
oh my resolution is to get

00:20:45.130 --> 00:20:47.010
more joy out of life.

00:20:47.010 --> 00:20:49.170
OK so what does that mean?

00:20:49.170 --> 00:20:50.960
I have no idea what
that means.

00:20:50.960 --> 00:20:52.730
And the person making that
resolution, I don't think,

00:20:52.730 --> 00:20:53.470
really has a good idea.

00:20:53.470 --> 00:20:55.850
Or I want to be less
stressed out.

00:20:55.850 --> 00:20:57.560
OK, why?

00:20:57.560 --> 00:20:58.580
Do you feel like you
need more sleep?

00:20:58.580 --> 00:21:00.020
Do you feel like you never
see your friends?

00:21:00.020 --> 00:21:01.505
Do you feel like you need to
make time to exercise?

00:21:01.505 --> 00:21:05.160
Do you feel like you need to
have time to write a novel?

00:21:05.160 --> 00:21:06.570
Why?

00:21:06.570 --> 00:21:08.590
Do you feel like you yell your
kids too much in the morning?

00:21:08.590 --> 00:21:09.700
Do you feel like you're
hitting the

00:21:09.700 --> 00:21:10.820
snooze button too much?

00:21:10.820 --> 00:21:12.520
Do you feel like you're eating
too much junk food?

00:21:12.520 --> 00:21:15.480
Do you feel like you're always
10 minutes late?

00:21:15.480 --> 00:21:17.830
Do you feel like you're letting
down your colleagues

00:21:17.830 --> 00:21:19.070
because you're always
late with projects?

00:21:19.070 --> 00:21:20.930
What do you mean by
stressed out?

00:21:20.930 --> 00:21:24.110
Because once you say what would
you actually change?

00:21:24.110 --> 00:21:26.200
Then you can say to yourself
this is what I'm actually

00:21:26.200 --> 00:21:28.250
going to do, and then you know
whether you did it or not.

00:21:28.250 --> 00:21:31.090
And if you consistently can't do
it maybe you need to set a

00:21:31.090 --> 00:21:32.400
different resolution.

00:21:32.400 --> 00:21:37.760
Or if you can do it are you
seeing any beneficial change?

00:21:37.760 --> 00:21:44.740
Because to bring about change
you really need to figure out

00:21:44.740 --> 00:21:47.720
what would actually
be different?

00:21:47.720 --> 00:21:54.980
And not just think about vague
aims without a plan for how

00:21:54.980 --> 00:21:57.420
you could bring them
about in real life.

00:21:57.420 --> 00:21:59.730
SHAREE: One of the biggest
things I got from your books

00:21:59.730 --> 00:22:00.750
was exactly that.

00:22:00.750 --> 00:22:04.890
That happiness can be broken
down into actionable items

00:22:04.890 --> 00:22:07.310
that you evaluate yourself
on, on a daily basis.

00:22:07.310 --> 00:22:09.890
And in that sense it sounds a
lot like the OKRs we set for

00:22:09.890 --> 00:22:12.630
ourselves every quarter.

00:22:12.630 --> 00:22:16.370
And I think it makes for a
perfect parallel there.

00:22:16.370 --> 00:22:20.340
I actually did start off my
own Happiness Project.

00:22:20.340 --> 00:22:25.490
I did pause it for a little
while, but what did come out

00:22:25.490 --> 00:22:27.780
of it is that I am participating
for the first

00:22:27.780 --> 00:22:29.030
time in NaNoWritMo.

00:22:31.510 --> 00:22:34.750
And I am, as of this morning,
6,000 words

00:22:34.750 --> 00:22:35.970
away from my 50,000.

00:22:35.970 --> 00:22:36.800
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Oh my gosh,
congratulations.

00:22:36.800 --> 00:22:38.100
SHAREE: Thank you very much.

00:22:38.100 --> 00:22:40.690
I see myself completing it
by the end of tomorrow.

00:22:40.690 --> 00:22:42.210
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Wow,
that's amazing.

00:22:42.210 --> 00:22:42.780
Well congratulations.

00:22:42.780 --> 00:22:44.350
SHAREE: Thank you.

00:22:44.350 --> 00:22:48.870
So I'm really hoping that a lot
of you go out there and

00:22:48.870 --> 00:22:51.710
look at your OKRs, create
daily ones for yourself.

00:22:51.710 --> 00:22:53.150
There's really a lot
that'll can out of

00:22:53.150 --> 00:22:54.300
having a happiness project.

