00:23:15.560 --> 00:23:19.770
But I'm 6,000 words away from
getting to the 50,000.

00:23:19.770 --> 00:23:21.820
It doesn't have to be a fully
coherent novel, really.

00:23:21.820 --> 00:23:23.350
It's really just
about writing.

00:23:23.350 --> 00:23:25.220
It's to get you through
the creative block.

00:23:25.220 --> 00:23:26.871
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:23:26.871 --> 00:23:28.210
SHAREE: Yes, exactly.

00:23:28.210 --> 00:23:29.990
I mean no one's expecting
to get theirs published.

00:23:29.990 --> 00:23:31.430
GRETCHEN RUBIN: If you're
interested, there's a book

00:23:31.430 --> 00:23:33.920
called "No Plot No Problem"
by Chris Baty where

00:23:33.920 --> 00:23:35.160
he lays this out.

00:23:35.160 --> 00:23:37.590
National Novel Writing Month
is when everybody--

00:23:37.590 --> 00:23:39.070
November is the month.

00:23:39.070 --> 00:23:43.330
Importantly, because it has 31
days, you have an extra day.

00:23:43.330 --> 00:23:44.300
That people do it.

00:23:44.300 --> 00:23:47.000
And there's screenwriting month,
blog starting, there's

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:48.200
a lot of offshoots.

00:23:48.200 --> 00:23:53.080
But I did it just in my own
month reading the book.

00:23:53.080 --> 00:23:57.050
But it's really if you're ever
attracted to kind of a boot

00:23:57.050 --> 00:24:02.410
camp start for something, it's
a way to just, like you say,

00:24:02.410 --> 00:24:07.990
get your creativity going by
just consistent productivity.

00:24:07.990 --> 00:24:09.430
and it's so much fun.

00:24:09.430 --> 00:24:11.260
It's really, really fun.

00:24:11.260 --> 00:24:15.150
I mean something like "The Great
Gatsby" was only like

00:24:15.150 --> 00:24:17.040
60, or 70,000 words long.

00:24:17.040 --> 00:24:18.950
So if you write 50,000
words in a month,

00:24:18.950 --> 00:24:20.710
that's a good start.

00:24:20.710 --> 00:24:22.450
But anyway, I really recommend
"No Plot No Problem".

00:24:22.450 --> 00:24:25.010
Because it goes through the
theory of how you should think

00:24:25.010 --> 00:24:27.290
about editing, how you should
think about outlining in

00:24:27.290 --> 00:24:30.170
preparation, and how this is
meant to spur creativity.

00:24:30.170 --> 00:24:31.910
Like why you would
do it this way.

00:24:31.910 --> 00:24:33.500
But it's tons of fun.

00:24:33.500 --> 00:24:34.830
SHAREE: Yeah, and you mentioned
in your book.

00:24:34.830 --> 00:24:36.320
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yes, I did.

00:24:36.320 --> 00:24:37.975
I really enjoyed it.

00:24:37.975 --> 00:24:40.210
SHAREE: So how long did the
habits you developed during

00:24:40.210 --> 00:24:42.900
the Happiness Project last once
you stopped doing the

00:24:42.900 --> 00:24:44.140
check marks?

00:24:44.140 --> 00:24:47.460
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Well, I still
do almost everything that I

00:24:47.460 --> 00:24:48.980
did, because they all
make me happier.

00:24:48.980 --> 00:24:50.950
And I'm less happy when
I break them.

00:24:50.950 --> 00:24:55.210
So for the most part either I
abandoned them right away,

00:24:55.210 --> 00:24:57.790
like the gratitude journal,
which drove me crazy.

00:24:57.790 --> 00:25:01.330
Though many people love
a gratitude journal.

00:25:01.330 --> 00:25:04.500
Almost everything I do and more,
way more, even than I

00:25:04.500 --> 00:25:09.240
write about in both
of the books.

00:25:09.240 --> 00:25:13.680
For me it's a way of thinking
about the way I behave that's

00:25:13.680 --> 00:25:16.040
very, very helpful.

00:25:16.040 --> 00:25:18.410
But it was helpful to do the
charts where I would check it

00:25:18.410 --> 00:25:21.120
off, because that kind of
accountability also is helpful

00:25:21.120 --> 00:25:23.710
because sometimes you want to
do something, or you want to

00:25:23.710 --> 00:25:25.570
make a change, and it just
falls out of your mind.

00:25:25.570 --> 00:25:27.020
You just don't think about it.

00:25:27.020 --> 00:25:28.660
Except for a couple
times a week.

00:25:28.660 --> 00:25:32.480
And so just even by reviewing
them once a day that helped me

00:25:32.480 --> 00:25:33.730
keep them active in my mind.

00:25:36.680 --> 00:25:39.220
So for instance, now if I'm in
a conversation and I start to

00:25:39.220 --> 00:25:42.310
gossip I may continue to
gossip, I may break the

00:25:42.310 --> 00:25:44.710
resolution because it's hard not
to gossip, because it's so

00:25:44.710 --> 00:25:45.410
fun to gossip.

00:25:45.410 --> 00:25:48.570
But the sirens are going off,
are the horns are blaring

00:25:48.570 --> 00:25:51.230
being hey, that's a
resolution here.

00:25:51.230 --> 00:25:52.460
Are you going to break
your resolution?

00:25:52.460 --> 00:25:52.950
Are you going to go?

00:25:52.950 --> 00:25:54.660
You're right up the line,
are you going to go?

00:25:54.660 --> 00:25:58.250
So I don't forget about
it, and do it.

00:25:58.250 --> 00:26:01.360
I'm aware whether
I am or am not.

00:26:01.360 --> 00:26:03.970
Under-react to a problem, that's
one of my resolutions.

00:26:03.970 --> 00:26:07.350
And sometimes I just take it
all the way up to 11, but I

00:26:07.350 --> 00:26:11.540
know that's what I'm doing,
and usually I regret it,

00:26:11.540 --> 00:26:13.670
because it's better
to under-react.

00:26:13.670 --> 00:26:15.880
But it's always in my mind that
there is a resolution

00:26:15.880 --> 00:26:18.310
there that I am either
keeping or breaking.

00:26:18.310 --> 00:26:21.250
SHAREE: So something about the
initial checking off process

00:26:21.250 --> 00:26:22.780
really helps you get
those things in

00:26:22.780 --> 00:26:22.890
your mind and ingrained?

00:26:22.890 --> 00:26:25.300
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Just to
reinforce it, yeah.

00:26:25.300 --> 00:26:26.850
Actually my next book--

00:26:26.850 --> 00:26:28.220
speaking of habits--

00:26:28.220 --> 00:26:29.500
is going to be all
about habits.

00:26:29.500 --> 00:26:32.070
Because I realize that habits
are really the prequel to a

00:26:32.070 --> 00:26:32.630
happiness project.

00:26:32.630 --> 00:26:34.850
Because if you have good
habits it's so much

00:26:34.850 --> 00:26:36.390
easier to be happy.

00:26:36.390 --> 00:26:40.300
And if you have bad habits
it's a stumbling block.

00:26:40.300 --> 00:26:43.760
So the idea of how do you get
yourself in the habit of doing

00:26:43.760 --> 00:26:47.445
anything is something that I am
now completely obsessed by.

00:26:47.445 --> 00:26:48.555
SHAREE: That sounds
fascinating.

00:26:48.555 --> 00:26:49.300
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Stay tuned.

00:26:49.300 --> 00:26:50.990
SHAREE: Cool.

00:26:50.990 --> 00:26:54.830
So one mantra you repeat often
in your book is that you can

00:26:54.830 --> 00:26:57.870
only change your behavior
and not that of others.

00:26:57.870 --> 00:27:00.740
And I'm sure that all of the
resolutions you set for

00:27:00.740 --> 00:27:02.460
yourself reflect that.

00:27:02.460 --> 00:27:05.090
And why is it that important?

00:27:05.090 --> 00:27:07.080
It also screams unfair.

00:27:07.080 --> 00:27:10.330
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yeah, well, it
is a sad truth of happiness

00:27:10.330 --> 00:27:12.890
that the only person you
can change is yourself.

00:27:12.890 --> 00:27:17.880
Because it's so easy to think
I would be happier if other

00:27:17.880 --> 00:27:20.810
people would behave properly.

00:27:20.810 --> 00:27:23.160
And to have a long list of
resolutions for other people

00:27:23.160 --> 00:27:24.840
to follow, perfectly
reasonable.

00:27:24.840 --> 00:27:26.360
But it doesn't work like that.

00:27:26.360 --> 00:27:29.280
Alas, you can only
take yourself.

00:27:29.280 --> 00:27:33.180
But I did find that when I
change the atmosphere around

00:27:33.180 --> 00:27:33.890
me changes.

00:27:33.890 --> 00:27:37.450
And when I change, a
relationship changes.

00:27:37.450 --> 00:27:40.630
And very often I was able to
bring about larger changes

00:27:40.630 --> 00:27:43.230
just by thinking about what I
could do differently, or how I

00:27:43.230 --> 00:27:44.480
could change.

00:27:46.650 --> 00:27:49.570
And sometimes people say to me
well I really wanted to do a

00:27:49.570 --> 00:27:52.590
happiness project, but my
spouse doesn't want to.

00:27:52.590 --> 00:27:55.260
Or my roommates don't want
to, or whatever.

00:27:55.260 --> 00:27:57.430
And the fact is nobody--

00:27:57.430 --> 00:28:00.950
my husband, he doesn't even make
New Year's resolutions.

00:28:00.950 --> 00:28:03.150
I mean he would never do
something like this.

00:28:03.150 --> 00:28:04.280
It's just not his nature.

00:28:04.280 --> 00:28:07.980
I mean he feels like a martyr
to happiness at this point.

00:28:07.980 --> 00:28:10.160
But you don't need to.

00:28:10.160 --> 00:28:11.690
It's not something where
you need other people's

00:28:11.690 --> 00:28:12.330
cooperation.

00:28:12.330 --> 00:28:16.290
Because really it is something
that is all about what can you

00:28:16.290 --> 00:28:17.540
do differently?

00:28:22.020 --> 00:28:24.360
Sometimes I think you can all
agree to do something

00:28:24.360 --> 00:28:28.070
differently, but I think it
should be the rare exception.

00:28:28.070 --> 00:28:34.570
Rather than thinking that
handing out ideas for other

00:28:34.570 --> 00:28:37.830
people, or thinking about how
other people should change to

00:28:37.830 --> 00:28:44.332
bring about change it's
just not possible.

00:28:44.332 --> 00:28:49.480
SHAREE: There's an interesting
and sad fact that you mention

00:28:49.480 --> 00:28:52.690
in your second book.

00:28:52.690 --> 00:28:55.280
It says that research found
that perceived time passes

00:28:55.280 --> 00:28:58.220
more quickly as you
grow older.

00:28:58.220 --> 00:29:01.250
And I think that ties back to
what you mentioned earlier

00:29:01.250 --> 00:29:04.950
about growth, and a rich
and vivid experience.

00:29:04.950 --> 00:29:05.850
Can you tell us more?

00:29:05.850 --> 00:29:07.960
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yeah, it's this
very interesting thing

00:29:07.960 --> 00:29:09.770
that, as people grow older--

00:29:09.770 --> 00:29:11.860
and I'm sure everybody's
experienced this-- that your

00:29:11.860 --> 00:29:14.270
perception of time changes.

00:29:14.270 --> 00:29:17.940
And so looking back at your
life, the first 21 years will

00:29:17.940 --> 00:29:21.600
be much will seem like it took
a much bigger percentage of

00:29:21.600 --> 00:29:24.810
your existence.

00:29:24.810 --> 00:29:26.960
And it narrows as
you get older.

00:29:26.960 --> 00:29:30.500
So between 60 and 80 is much
less than it actually is in

00:29:30.500 --> 00:29:33.090
terms of where it is
on the pie chart.

00:29:33.090 --> 00:29:35.440
And one of the things you can do
to counter this is that if

00:29:35.440 --> 00:29:38.260
you do something very novel
and challenging, your

00:29:38.260 --> 00:29:40.580
experience of time slows.

00:29:40.580 --> 00:29:42.900
Because there's so much new
information that you're

00:29:42.900 --> 00:29:43.750
processing.

00:29:43.750 --> 00:29:46.350
And I remember a friend of mine
saying that he was really

00:29:46.350 --> 00:29:48.490
happy when he and his
wife had a baby.

00:29:48.490 --> 00:29:50.490
He said because life was rushing
by so quickly, but

00:29:50.490 --> 00:29:52.960
when she was born it was
like time stood still.

00:29:52.960 --> 00:29:56.380
And her first month of life felt
like two or three years.

00:29:56.380 --> 00:29:58.620
And when I was working at the
Federal Communications

00:29:58.620 --> 00:30:00.590
Commission it was so intense.

00:30:00.590 --> 00:30:03.050
There was so much going on, it
was so new, there were so many

00:30:03.050 --> 00:30:04.230
people, there was so
much that I had

00:30:04.230 --> 00:30:05.920
never experienced before.

00:30:05.920 --> 00:30:07.540
I mean I was only there
for 14 months.

00:30:07.540 --> 00:30:09.770
But it feels like as
long as law school,

00:30:09.770 --> 00:30:10.710
which was three years.

00:30:10.710 --> 00:30:13.960
Because law school was pretty
familiar, and one year was

00:30:13.960 --> 00:30:15.390
pretty much like the next.

00:30:15.390 --> 00:30:16.950
Whereas this was a whole
different thing.

00:30:16.950 --> 00:30:19.110
Or the time when
I was clerking.

00:30:19.110 --> 00:30:21.490
It just felt like so
much was happening

00:30:21.490 --> 00:30:22.500
because it was so new.

00:30:22.500 --> 00:30:24.940
And I've been thinking about
this a lot for myself, for my

00:30:24.940 --> 00:30:25.750
own Happiness Project.

00:30:25.750 --> 00:30:29.260
Because I feel like time is
going by so quickly, and I

00:30:29.260 --> 00:30:30.000
don't like it.

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:32.080
I don't like this feeling that
everything is racing by.

00:30:32.080 --> 00:30:35.520
So I keep thinking, well, what
can I do to shake myself up?

00:30:35.520 --> 00:30:36.790
But the problem is I
don't want a new

00:30:36.790 --> 00:30:37.990
career, I love my career.

00:30:37.990 --> 00:30:39.250
I don't want to have
another baby.

00:30:39.250 --> 00:30:41.020
And I already have two children,
so it wouldn't even

00:30:41.020 --> 00:30:43.585
be that novel and challenging
probably, for these purposes.

00:30:43.585 --> 00:30:45.100
It would have other
advantages, but it

00:30:45.100 --> 00:30:47.100
wouldn't with this.

00:30:47.100 --> 00:30:49.570
I don't want to move, I want
to live in New York City.

00:30:49.570 --> 00:30:51.770
I don't even want to live
five blocks away from

00:30:51.770 --> 00:30:52.790
where I live now.

00:30:52.790 --> 00:30:53.600
So I'm trying to think.

00:30:53.600 --> 00:30:55.960
And there's really nothing that
I want to do, like to

00:30:55.960 --> 00:30:57.230
learn to speak French.

00:30:57.230 --> 00:30:59.150
I don't really want to learn
to speak French.

00:30:59.150 --> 00:31:01.120
I wish I wanted to learn to
speak French, but be Gretchen

00:31:01.120 --> 00:31:03.620
and don't waste your time
learning to speak French.

00:31:03.620 --> 00:31:05.160
So I've been really struggling
with this.

00:31:05.160 --> 00:31:07.690
One of things about starting a
blog that was amazing for me--

00:31:07.690 --> 00:31:11.060
which I didn't really know that
this was going to happen,

00:31:11.060 --> 00:31:12.880
but it did serve that
function for me.

00:31:12.880 --> 00:31:15.190
Because I had never done
anything like that before.

00:31:15.190 --> 00:31:16.400
I didn't know anything
about it.

00:31:16.400 --> 00:31:18.350
And so it was huge,
it was new.

00:31:18.350 --> 00:31:20.250
It was this whole new
identity for me.

00:31:20.250 --> 00:31:22.080
A whole new group of people that
I was hanging out with, a

00:31:22.080 --> 00:31:23.960
whole new skill that I added.

00:31:23.960 --> 00:31:25.950
And that really did
enrich that time.

00:31:25.950 --> 00:31:28.300
But now I feel like it's
become part of me

00:31:28.300 --> 00:31:29.780
and part of my day.

00:31:29.780 --> 00:31:32.170
It doesn't serve that novel
and challenging function.

00:31:32.170 --> 00:31:35.230
So I've really been thinking
well what could I do?

00:31:35.230 --> 00:31:36.360
Like get a pet?

00:31:36.360 --> 00:31:37.830
I don't want a dog.

00:31:37.830 --> 00:31:38.360
I don't know.

00:31:38.360 --> 00:31:40.830
So any suggestions I welcome.

00:31:40.830 --> 00:31:43.570
Because there is something about
the atmosphere of growth

00:31:43.570 --> 00:31:46.080
that serves this function
of making life

00:31:46.080 --> 00:31:47.630
more rich, more dense.

00:31:47.630 --> 00:31:49.075
Probably moving to a
foreign country.

00:31:52.570 --> 00:31:53.910
And the more foreign,
the better.

00:31:53.910 --> 00:31:58.700
The more dense and rich that
experience would be.

00:31:58.700 --> 00:32:01.275
And like I said I don't even
want to leave my neighborhood.

00:32:04.020 --> 00:32:05.690
But there's got to be other
ways to do that.

00:32:05.690 --> 00:32:09.030
So that's something that I'm
thinking about, because it's a

00:32:09.030 --> 00:32:10.250
very real aspect of life.

00:32:10.250 --> 00:32:12.470
And it is something that
we can affect.

00:32:12.470 --> 00:32:16.050
SHAREE: You also talk about
unscheduled free time.

00:32:16.050 --> 00:32:18.690
And you say that it's very
important for children, for

00:32:18.690 --> 00:32:20.470
creativity, and other
such things.

00:32:20.470 --> 00:32:21.895
How about for adults?

00:32:21.895 --> 00:32:23.540
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Absolutely,
but I would say maybe

00:32:23.540 --> 00:32:24.980
scheduling free time.

00:32:24.980 --> 00:32:27.910
Scheduling unscheduled time,
as paradoxical as that is.

00:32:27.910 --> 00:32:29.830
You need to schedule
unscheduled time.

00:32:29.830 --> 00:32:33.680
And I'm sure that I am talking
to the people who suffer from

00:32:33.680 --> 00:32:36.980
this, which is this feeling
like everything is flowing

00:32:36.980 --> 00:32:38.120
into everything else.

00:32:38.120 --> 00:32:40.450
Either you are working, or you
could be working, or you

00:32:40.450 --> 00:32:41.170
should be working.

00:32:41.170 --> 00:32:43.700
Or maybe you're kind of working
and you're not really

00:32:43.700 --> 00:32:45.640
at leisure, because you know
you could be working or you

00:32:45.640 --> 00:32:46.890
should be working.

00:32:49.500 --> 00:32:50.960
But then there's a lot of
times when you could be

00:32:50.960 --> 00:32:52.000
working, or should be working.

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:53.590
And you're even at work,
but you're not working.

00:32:53.590 --> 00:32:55.930
But that doesn't feel
like leisure.

00:32:55.930 --> 00:33:02.810
And to think about giving
yourself a quitting time.

00:33:02.810 --> 00:33:04.580
It used to be nine
to five, right?

00:33:04.580 --> 00:33:06.070
Five o'clock was
quitting time.

00:33:06.070 --> 00:33:07.930
That doesn't happen anymore.

00:33:07.930 --> 00:33:11.640
We all walk around with a
cubicle in our pocket.

00:33:11.640 --> 00:33:14.030
So what I do is every day, and
every day it's a different

00:33:14.030 --> 00:33:16.790
time because my schedule is
very different every day.

00:33:16.790 --> 00:33:20.560
Is I say this time
is quitting time.

00:33:20.560 --> 00:33:23.020
And after quitting time,
I don't work anymore.

00:33:23.020 --> 00:33:24.990
I don't check my email.

00:33:24.990 --> 00:33:27.305
I don't work.

00:33:27.305 --> 00:33:30.150
And I try not even to do like
household tasks, because I

00:33:30.150 --> 00:33:32.180
want it to be leisure time.

00:33:32.180 --> 00:33:34.000
And it's really important.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:37.830
Or maybe on the weekend you'll
say from 11 to two is

00:33:37.830 --> 00:33:40.200
playtime, and I'm going to
do just what I feel like.

00:33:40.200 --> 00:33:42.640
I have a friend who's
a novelist.

00:33:42.640 --> 00:33:47.340
And on Sundays he does not
even read nonfiction.

00:33:47.340 --> 00:33:48.490
He only reads novels.

00:33:48.490 --> 00:33:50.130
Which is his work but
also his play.

00:33:50.130 --> 00:33:52.670
But he doesn't do any work,
and he won't even read the

00:33:52.670 --> 00:33:55.720
newspaper or read a biography.

00:33:55.720 --> 00:33:59.140
Because he wants to have
total playtime.

00:33:59.140 --> 00:34:01.260
And then people use freedom.

00:34:01.260 --> 00:34:06.250
People have all different ways
of figuring out how to break

00:34:06.250 --> 00:34:07.720
free, and to give themselves
free time.

00:34:07.720 --> 00:34:10.429
But I think there's sort of
a feeling like I will just

00:34:10.429 --> 00:34:13.100
spontaneously have fun
in my free time.

00:34:13.100 --> 00:34:14.770
Or I'll do that when I
have some free time.

00:34:14.770 --> 00:34:17.710
But you don't have any free
time, like for 10 years.

00:34:17.710 --> 00:34:20.460
So if you want to have a
sense of leisure you

00:34:20.460 --> 00:34:23.239
have to build it in.

00:34:23.239 --> 00:34:27.120
Force yourself to wander,
make time.

00:34:27.120 --> 00:34:30.370
My daughter is in second grade
and they have choice time.

00:34:30.370 --> 00:34:32.710
And I love the idea
of choice time.

00:34:32.710 --> 00:34:35.480
Because you can just choose
whatever you want to do.

00:34:35.480 --> 00:34:39.310
But I think some people go weeks
and months maybe without

00:34:39.310 --> 00:34:42.030
really having choice time.

00:34:42.030 --> 00:34:46.179
They're just picking
between duty and

00:34:46.179 --> 00:34:48.190
sort of the bad trance.

00:34:48.190 --> 00:34:49.614
You know the bad trance.

00:34:49.614 --> 00:34:52.030
When you're clicking around
the internet, or watching

00:34:52.030 --> 00:34:55.620
television, or flipping through
a magazine that you're

00:34:55.620 --> 00:34:58.450
not even that interested in, or
you're eating in front of

00:34:58.450 --> 00:35:02.710
the refrigerator, and you're
in the bad trance.

00:35:02.710 --> 00:35:03.900
Usually, if you're in the
bad trance it means you

00:35:03.900 --> 00:35:05.120
should go to bed.

00:35:05.120 --> 00:35:08.290
The bad trance is a sign
of being too tired.

00:35:08.290 --> 00:35:11.480
So always go to sleep if you're
in the bad trance.

00:35:11.480 --> 00:35:14.590
SHAREE: Bad trance sounds a
lot like trading long-term

00:35:14.590 --> 00:35:17.652
happiness for short.

00:35:17.652 --> 00:35:20.320
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Well
that's another

00:35:20.320 --> 00:35:21.700
tension within happiness.

00:35:21.700 --> 00:35:23.680
Which is thinking about what
makes you happy in the moment,

00:35:23.680 --> 00:35:25.430
and thinking about what's
going to make you

00:35:25.430 --> 00:35:28.520
happy in the future.

00:35:28.520 --> 00:35:30.220
I did the bad trance
is sort of neither.

00:35:30.220 --> 00:35:32.750
It's not very satisfying in the
present, and it certainly

00:35:32.750 --> 00:35:33.780
doesn't pay off in the future.

00:35:33.780 --> 00:35:34.395
SHAREE: It's even worse?

00:35:34.395 --> 00:35:37.290
GRETCHEN RUBIN: And so if you're
in the bad trance, or

00:35:37.290 --> 00:35:38.640
you notice that you're spending
a lot of time in bad

00:35:38.640 --> 00:35:43.870
trance you need to think about
what could I do differently?

00:35:43.870 --> 00:35:47.730
Either to have more short-term
pleasure by just doing

00:35:47.730 --> 00:35:51.270
something that's going to be
more fun in the moment, or by

00:35:51.270 --> 00:35:53.440
thinking about how I could use
my time in a way that's going

00:35:53.440 --> 00:35:54.770
to pay off more in the end.

00:35:54.770 --> 00:35:56.760
Because the thing is, a lot of
times, the things that payoff

00:35:56.760 --> 00:35:58.660
the most in the end
are a lot of work.

00:35:58.660 --> 00:36:01.340
Like let's say you were going
to plan a big holiday party.

00:36:01.340 --> 00:36:03.610
I mean it's a lot of errands,
it's a lot of planning, it's a

00:36:03.610 --> 00:36:06.230
lot of tidying up the house.

00:36:06.230 --> 00:36:11.090
There's a lot of parts of it
that are not that much fun.

00:36:11.090 --> 00:36:13.700
But in the end that's the kind
of thing that's going to bring

00:36:13.700 --> 00:36:14.580
you a lot of happiness.

00:36:14.580 --> 00:36:18.990
And so it's better to spend an
hour doing party planning

00:36:18.990 --> 00:36:22.520
chores than it is to spend that
hour in the bad trance.

00:36:22.520 --> 00:36:24.990
Even though at the moment that
you're doing it it feels

00:36:24.990 --> 00:36:29.220
mildly diverting.

00:36:29.220 --> 00:36:34.210
SHAREE: I try to distinguish
between the two by the fact

00:36:34.210 --> 00:36:37.000
that one leaves you
with memories,

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:37.830
and the other doesn't.

00:36:37.830 --> 00:36:42.900
So you might watch a whole
series of something on Hulu.

00:36:42.900 --> 00:36:45.310
And at the moment you're
enjoying it.

00:36:45.310 --> 00:36:47.950
But when you look back three
weeks later you don't even

00:36:47.950 --> 00:36:49.470
remember that you
really did it.

00:36:49.470 --> 00:36:51.290
GRETCHEN RUBIN: That
is a great test.

00:36:51.290 --> 00:36:52.900
Because I think about energy.

00:36:52.900 --> 00:36:54.960
Like is something energizing
or draining?

00:36:54.960 --> 00:36:58.170
But memories is a very
good thing too.

00:36:58.170 --> 00:37:01.210
Though now that's making me call
into question my ambition

00:37:01.210 --> 00:37:05.920
to watch all of Homeland within
the next couple weeks.

00:37:05.920 --> 00:37:07.790
But I think that's a
really good point.

00:37:07.790 --> 00:37:11.830
Is it something that is
going to be adding?

00:37:11.830 --> 00:37:14.060
Or is it just something that's
so ephemeral that you're not

00:37:14.060 --> 00:37:16.070
even going to remember
that you did it.

00:37:16.070 --> 00:37:17.670
And then the other test
is the energy.

00:37:17.670 --> 00:37:20.150
Do you walk away from it
feeling energized?

00:37:20.150 --> 00:37:23.531
Or do you walk away from
it feeling drained?

00:37:23.531 --> 00:37:25.830
SHAREE: One other thing
that you mention--

00:37:25.830 --> 00:37:28.630
it's also a sad fact, and it's
in your second book.

00:37:28.630 --> 00:37:32.300
It says that small children
laugh about 400 times, and

00:37:32.300 --> 00:37:35.350
adults laugh about
17 times a day.

00:37:35.350 --> 00:37:37.410
And I saw, and I was just
shaking my head.

00:37:37.410 --> 00:37:39.000
And it's very true though.

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:42.070
So since you became aware of
this fact have you noticed

00:37:42.070 --> 00:37:43.100
yourself laughing more?

00:37:43.100 --> 00:37:45.985
And what do you do to fix it?

00:37:45.985 --> 00:37:48.330
GRETCHEN RUBIN: I'm sure you can
tell this, but I'm a very

00:37:48.330 --> 00:37:52.470
tightly-wound irritable
type personality.

00:37:52.470 --> 00:37:56.820
And I can take it to 11,
like in a flash.

00:37:56.820 --> 00:37:58.170
I have this thing,
my mean face.

00:37:58.170 --> 00:38:00.540
Which apparently is this
Medusa-like terrifying mean

00:38:00.540 --> 00:38:03.340
face that I make.

00:38:03.340 --> 00:38:05.840
And so many, many of my
resolutions are aimed at

00:38:05.840 --> 00:38:08.840
trying to be more lighthearted,
more calm, more

00:38:08.840 --> 00:38:11.840
patient, more fun, taking
time for projects.

00:38:11.840 --> 00:38:13.770
Again it comes back to
this idea of time.

00:38:13.770 --> 00:38:16.350
Taking time to be silly, not
constantly walking around

00:38:16.350 --> 00:38:20.460
marching, or barking out orders,
or crossing things off

00:38:20.460 --> 00:38:21.050
the to-do list.

00:38:21.050 --> 00:38:22.490
But to make time to have
fun, and to goof

00:38:22.490 --> 00:38:24.120
around and be silly.

00:38:24.120 --> 00:38:29.320
So that kind of fact really did
make me focus on how can I

00:38:29.320 --> 00:38:31.430
be more fun?

00:38:31.430 --> 00:38:33.850
And it's interesting just
talking in a workplace.

00:38:33.850 --> 00:38:37.620
There's a lot of studies showing
that just having fun

00:38:37.620 --> 00:38:40.710
in the workplace is important,
and levity.

00:38:40.710 --> 00:38:42.600
There's an interesting book
called "The Levity Effect".

00:38:42.600 --> 00:38:44.470
And by levity, it doesn't it
mean people are cracking jokes

00:38:44.470 --> 00:38:45.490
and actually being funny.

00:38:45.490 --> 00:38:49.330
Because actually being
funny is hard.

00:38:49.330 --> 00:38:52.250
But people can be lighthearted,
and they can see

00:38:52.250 --> 00:38:54.260
the funny side, especially
when things go wrong.

00:38:54.260 --> 00:38:57.780
Or they can under-react to
problems, or they can have a

00:38:57.780 --> 00:39:03.390
sense of just laughing, and
a sense of lightness.

00:39:03.390 --> 00:39:04.820
That is a social lubricant.

00:39:04.820 --> 00:39:07.280
It helps people work with
difficult personalities, that

00:39:07.280 --> 00:39:09.670
helps people deal with anxieties
and tensions.

00:39:09.670 --> 00:39:11.950
And so it really is worth
something that.

00:39:11.950 --> 00:39:14.650
And also if you're in a conflict
with somebody, if you

00:39:14.650 --> 00:39:20.260
can not make sarcastic asides,
which is the worst

00:39:20.260 --> 00:39:20.840
thing you can do.

00:39:20.840 --> 00:39:23.150
But if you can find a way to
joke about it or to relieve

00:39:23.150 --> 00:39:27.550
the tension it's really,
really helpful.

00:39:27.550 --> 00:39:33.380
If you're in a bad place it's
very hard to see the funny

00:39:33.380 --> 00:39:35.490
side, and to be lighthearted.

00:39:35.490 --> 00:39:37.320
But it really, really helps.

00:39:37.320 --> 00:39:40.120
And so to think about how to
get more laughing, and more

00:39:40.120 --> 00:39:43.460
joking around, and
more playing, it

00:39:43.460 --> 00:39:44.340
makes your life happier.

00:39:44.340 --> 00:39:46.830
And I think it also makes
you more effective

00:39:46.830 --> 00:39:49.555
in almost any realm.

00:39:49.555 --> 00:39:50.710
SHAREE: That's going to know.

00:39:50.710 --> 00:39:54.690
Try to beat 17.

00:39:54.690 --> 00:39:55.390
Any questions?

00:39:55.390 --> 00:39:56.640
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:39:59.355 --> 00:40:01.020
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Or we can just
