00:41:41.510 --> 00:41:44.780
So for "Happier at Home" I did
this behind-the-scenes video,

00:41:44.780 --> 00:41:45.640
which was so much fun.

00:41:45.640 --> 00:41:48.310
And I showed some of the
things that I talk

00:41:48.310 --> 00:41:49.080
about in the book.

00:41:49.080 --> 00:41:50.610
Just for fun, it was just
this little fun

00:41:50.610 --> 00:41:52.240
extra that I created.

00:41:52.240 --> 00:41:54.590
And one of the things that
I show is my empty shelf,

00:41:54.590 --> 00:41:57.060
because so many people ask
about the empty shelf.

00:41:57.060 --> 00:42:00.230
And the fact is it
sounds so weird.

00:42:00.230 --> 00:42:02.880
Like why does it matter to
have an empty shelf?

00:42:02.880 --> 00:42:07.790
And yet it really catches
people's imagination.

00:42:07.790 --> 00:42:11.140
And so many people have told
me how much they love their

00:42:11.140 --> 00:42:12.280
empty shelf.

00:42:12.280 --> 00:42:15.440
There is something
about that space.

00:42:15.440 --> 00:42:17.810
Making that space, holding that

00:42:17.810 --> 00:42:20.270
space, having that margin.

00:42:20.270 --> 00:42:23.700
Thoreau said I love having a
broad margin to my life.

00:42:23.700 --> 00:42:26.850
And there's something about an
empty shelf that gives you

00:42:26.850 --> 00:42:28.770
that feeling of having
a margin.

00:42:28.770 --> 00:42:30.570
Especially think in someplace
like New York City where you

00:42:30.570 --> 00:42:34.860
feel like every little inch has
to have an Ikea thing, so

00:42:34.860 --> 00:42:37.070
you can cram as much stuff
in there as possible.

00:42:37.070 --> 00:42:39.330
It's nice just to have your
empty shelf, you're like I got

00:42:39.330 --> 00:42:41.660
plenty of room, I got
my empty shelf.

00:42:41.660 --> 00:42:43.720
SHAREE: And why do you
think the physical

00:42:43.720 --> 00:42:44.955
environment is so important?

00:42:44.955 --> 00:42:47.210
GRETCHEN RUBIN: This
is a mystery to me.

00:42:47.210 --> 00:42:51.180
I'm constantly astonished why
it is that outer order

00:42:51.180 --> 00:42:53.900
contributes to inner calm to
the degree that it does.

00:42:53.900 --> 00:42:56.970
It just doesn't seem like it
should matter that much.

00:42:56.970 --> 00:42:59.220
And yet, I feel-- and over and
over people have told me that

00:42:59.220 --> 00:43:00.490
they feel the same way.

00:43:00.490 --> 00:43:03.550
That there is something about
creating outer order that

00:43:03.550 --> 00:43:07.080
makes people feel calmer and
more energetic, more creative,

00:43:07.080 --> 00:43:09.830
more in control of their life.

00:43:09.830 --> 00:43:13.270
And of all the resolutions when
people tell me oh I did a

00:43:13.270 --> 00:43:14.270
happiness project.

00:43:14.270 --> 00:43:15.640
I say what did you do?

00:43:15.640 --> 00:43:16.900
What did you do to be
happier at home?

00:43:16.900 --> 00:43:18.740
Or what did you do to boost
your happiness?

00:43:18.740 --> 00:43:20.070
This is the number
one resolution.

00:43:20.070 --> 00:43:22.020
And I'm not saying this is the
most significant resolution

00:43:22.020 --> 00:43:22.770
you could do.

00:43:22.770 --> 00:43:25.000
I'm just saying this seems to
be like the gateway drug

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:26.550
resolution.

00:43:26.550 --> 00:43:29.790
The resolution to
make your bed.

00:43:29.790 --> 00:43:32.980
How many people here regularly
make their bed?

00:43:32.980 --> 00:43:34.620
Not that many.

00:43:34.620 --> 00:43:37.930
How many people make their bed
in a hotel room on the morning

00:43:37.930 --> 00:43:38.700
they check out?

00:43:38.700 --> 00:43:39.490
All right.

00:43:39.490 --> 00:43:42.240
OK, we will talk later.

00:43:42.240 --> 00:43:46.670
There's something about these
little cleaning off your

00:43:46.670 --> 00:43:49.470
desks, filing things, cleaning
out your inbox.

00:43:49.470 --> 00:43:52.740
I know woman who told me she
throws away every single thing

00:43:52.740 --> 00:43:55.250
in her refrigerator
on January 1.

00:43:55.250 --> 00:43:56.100
It's like inbox 0.

00:43:56.100 --> 00:43:59.210
She just wants everything
gone.

00:43:59.210 --> 00:44:01.520
No even half-full bottle
of ketchup.

00:44:01.520 --> 00:44:05.760
There's something about outer
order, clear surfaces, empty

00:44:05.760 --> 00:44:10.650
shelves that helps people feel
calmer and more creative.

00:44:10.650 --> 00:44:12.474
SHAREE: You had a question?

00:44:12.474 --> 00:44:13.724
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:44:23.420 --> 00:44:25.020
are you more happy or
less happy when

00:44:25.020 --> 00:44:26.210
surround by happier people?

00:44:26.210 --> 00:44:26.700
That's one.

00:44:26.700 --> 00:44:29.540
And then does it make
you happier to make

00:44:29.540 --> 00:44:30.702
other people happy?

00:44:30.702 --> 00:44:32.840
GRETCHEN RUBIN: So the question
is are you happier if

00:44:32.840 --> 00:44:34.300
you're around happier people?

00:44:34.300 --> 00:44:37.640
And does it make you happy
to make others happy?

00:44:37.640 --> 00:44:40.300
There's something called
emotional contagion.

00:44:40.300 --> 00:44:44.870
And that's the term for it,
because we literally infect

00:44:44.870 --> 00:44:46.570
each other with our emotions.

00:44:46.570 --> 00:44:49.400
And so happy people help
make people happy.

00:44:49.400 --> 00:44:51.480
And so if you're around
happier people

00:44:51.480 --> 00:44:53.130
you will feel a lift.

00:44:53.130 --> 00:44:57.750
Unfortunately bad is stronger
than good, and negative

00:44:57.750 --> 00:45:00.040
emotions are more catching
than positive emotions.

00:45:00.040 --> 00:45:02.700
So if you're around people with
negative emotions you

00:45:02.700 --> 00:45:05.420
will also pick that
up very quickly,

00:45:05.420 --> 00:45:06.710
probably even more quickly.

00:45:06.710 --> 00:45:09.880
And we pick up these emotions
from each other in seconds.

00:45:09.880 --> 00:45:11.600
You could pick it up over the
phone, you could pick up just

00:45:11.600 --> 00:45:12.580
by looking at a photograph.

00:45:12.580 --> 00:45:14.690
So there's this constant
change of emotions that

00:45:14.690 --> 00:45:15.650
happens all the time.

00:45:15.650 --> 00:45:18.890
So being around happier people
will definitely help you be

00:45:18.890 --> 00:45:20.850
happier yourself.

00:45:20.850 --> 00:45:23.660
And then your next question was
does it make you happy to

00:45:23.660 --> 00:45:24.910
make other people happy?

00:45:27.320 --> 00:45:30.020
I have eight splendid truths
about happiness, and this is

00:45:30.020 --> 00:45:34.360
my second splendid truth, which
is a two-part truth.

00:45:34.360 --> 00:45:37.410
One of the best ways to make
yourself happy is to make

00:45:37.410 --> 00:45:39.040
other people happy.

00:45:39.040 --> 00:45:43.340
And this is one of the nicest
things about human nature.

00:45:43.340 --> 00:45:44.930
One of the best ways to make
yourself happy is to make

00:45:44.930 --> 00:45:45.900
other people happy.

00:45:45.900 --> 00:45:48.570
And some people argue that
this is a criticism.

00:45:48.570 --> 00:45:51.290
Like well no one can be truly
altruistic, because if you do

00:45:51.290 --> 00:45:52.310
something nice for
somebody else you

00:45:52.310 --> 00:45:53.460
just feel good yourself.

00:45:53.460 --> 00:45:56.546
Like, oh, well then
forget about it.

00:45:56.546 --> 00:45:59.490
I'm like this is the greatest
thing ever.

00:45:59.490 --> 00:46:02.150
I mean nothing makes me happier
than seeing me do

00:46:02.150 --> 00:46:03.820
something virtuous.

00:46:03.820 --> 00:46:07.560
And the fact that I find that
that makes me happy is good.

00:46:07.560 --> 00:46:10.950
So I see that is a positive
effect of human nature, not

00:46:10.950 --> 00:46:16.650
something that makes altruistic
behavior less

00:46:16.650 --> 00:46:19.190
admirable, or less laudable.

00:46:19.190 --> 00:46:21.710
But that's the first part of
the second splendid truth.

00:46:21.710 --> 00:46:23.900
And I think the second part of
the second splendid truth is

00:46:23.900 --> 00:46:26.580
also worth thinking about.

00:46:26.580 --> 00:46:29.430
So one of the best ways to make
yourself happy is to make

00:46:29.430 --> 00:46:30.480
other people happy.

00:46:30.480 --> 00:46:33.760
And one of the best ways to make
other people happy is to

00:46:33.760 --> 00:46:35.110
be happy yourself.

00:46:35.110 --> 00:46:36.960
And that gets to your
first point.

00:46:36.960 --> 00:46:40.280
Which is that a lot of times
we're more able to help other

00:46:40.280 --> 00:46:43.320
people be happy when we
are happier ourselves.

00:46:43.320 --> 00:46:46.660
Both because of emotional
contagion, that we help them.

00:46:46.660 --> 00:46:49.130
And also back to what I was
saying before is I think when

00:46:49.130 --> 00:46:50.530
we're happy we have
the emotional

00:46:50.530 --> 00:46:51.780
wherewithal to turn outwards.

00:46:54.160 --> 00:46:58.410
It is not selfish to want to be
happier, because if it is

00:46:58.410 --> 00:47:01.100
we should be selfish, if only
for selfless reasons.

00:47:01.100 --> 00:47:05.960
Because it's by being happier
ourselves that we give

00:47:05.960 --> 00:47:09.720
ourselves the wherewithal
to think about others.

00:47:12.648 --> 00:47:14.112
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:47:14.112 --> 00:47:15.881
First of all I think you're
